If the library of his own house could not supply him with the work· necessary for his literary purpose, doubtless they. could have been easily obtained from those of other houses belonging to the Order.

There is no reason to suppose that the word reclusus is here used in any other than its strict sense of an “ ankyr,” one who was shut up in a building specially appropriated to the purpose, and with a solemn service, by episcopal sanction3 aster which he could not leave his cell except in case of necessity or with the permission of the bishop.⁸ The expression in the preface, ‘⁴ Lenne sub regula paupertatis astrictus,’' probably refers to the vows taken on the occasion of his becoming a Dominican friar. The author has himself explained the word “ ankyr ” by' “ reoluse,'' and ren- dered it anachorita (p. 12). An instance of a friar being a recluse (indum) at Pagham in Sussex is mentioned in the will of St. Richard, Bishop os chichester* and we read of an anchoress within the nunnery of Clemen- thorpe, near York, in 1475.θ “

The author was, as we learn from his own words, bred, if not born, in Norfolk: “ comitatus N orthfolchie modum loquendi solum sum secutae, quem solum ab infancia didici, et solotenus plenius perfectiusque cognovi.” It may deserve observation that the peculiarities os the local dialect os the county should have been thus distinctly noticed at this period. We are, however, informed that, at an earlier time, Samson de Botington, abbot of St. Edmundsbury 1182-1211, was aecustomed to discourse to the people in the vernacular of Norfolk, the county in which he was born and bred, and that he had a pulpit for the purpose in the conventual church.‘¹
